# Course Outlines

## **CSC 1102 English Composition & Comprehension**  


| | | | | | | | 
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 1 |  
| **Course Code:** | CSC 1102 | **Course:** | English Composition & Comprehension | **Course Type:** | Core | | 
| **Course Area/Domain:** | GER | **Contact Hours:** | 3 hours/Week | **Credits:** | 3 | 
| **Lab Course Name:** | Nil | **Lab Course Code:** | Nil | **Pre-Requisite:** | None  | | 


|**Course Objectives**   |
|-|
| The core objective of this course is to enable students to become better listeners, readers and writers. This includes the ability to use appropriate words according to the context, construct coherent paragraphs through summarizing, paraphrasing, process analysis, cause and effect, comparison and contrast and making oral presentations effective through an understanding of non- verbal means of communication. | 

  
|**Course Description** |  
|-|  
| This comprehensive English language course aims to equip students with essential skills for effective communication, focusing on enhancing their abilities as listeners, readers, and writers. Through a structured curriculum covering topics such as paragraph and essay writing, summarizing, paraphrasing, expository and argumentative writing, data analysis, punctuation, reading comprehension, and vocabulary building, students will develop a strong foundation in using language appropriately, constructing coherent paragraphs and essays, and delivering engaging oral presentations. | 

 
**Text/Reference Books**   
| | |
|-|-|  
| 1. | Real Writing with Readings by Susan Anker (Sixth Edition) |
| 2. | 7 habits of highly effective teenagers, Sean Covey, 1st Edition 2006. | 

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---|
| 1 | Introduction Session, Warming-up, Course Outline Orientation |
| 2 | Reading between the lines Reading for Meaning and Understanding Reading for Details. |
| 3 | Paragraph Writing/Topic Sentence/Supporting Evidence/Concluding Sentence/ Cohesion/Coherence. |
| 4 | Structuring an essay/Thesis Statement and Main Ideas/Paragraphing and Cohesion/ Describing a place, person, thing, idea, etc./Applying Descriptive Writing Strategies. |
| 5 | Narrative Writing/Developing Picture Stories/Writing accounts and stories/Making Mind Map/ Characters/ Rising Action/ Climax/Falling Action/Personification/ Imagery/ Flashback |
| 6 | Summarizing/Reading for Meaning/Reading for Ideas/Identifying Key Ideas/Avoiding Block lifting |
| 7 | Paraphrasing: Rewriting to eliminate plagiarism/Reading for Main Idea/Identifying Key Ideas/Changing the Order of Information/ Removing Redundancy/Giving Citation |
| 8 | Midterm |
| 9 | Expository writing, looking at a discussion topic in a balanced way, essay writing. |
| 10 | Argumentative Writing, arguing for both sides while taking a clear stance. |
| 11 | Studying and analyzing data, Putting it in shape using appropriate language and structure. |
| 12 | Punctuation and Parts of Speech, Discussion on punctuation marks i.e. Full Stop/Comma/Exclamation, Mark/Question, Mark/Colon/Semicolon/Speech Marks/Parentheses Reinforcement of all parts of speech. |
| 13 | Reading Comprehension Skimming/Scanning/ Inferring/ Evaluating Deduction and Induction. |
| 14 | Vocabulary Building Synonyms and Antonyms Homonyms and Homophones. |
| 15 | Listening Comprehension Listening for specific details, Listening for Gist. |

**COURSE LEARNING OUTCOMES (CLOs)**  
| **CLO** | **Description** | **Domain** | **BT Level** |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Demonstrate comprehension and critical analysis of written texts,including skimming,scanning, and identifyingkey ideas. | C | 2 |
| 2 | Apply effective writing strategies in paragraphs, essays, and various compositions with proper structure, cohesion, and coherence. | C | 3 |
| 3 | Utilize paraphrasing, summarizing, and proper punctuation to communicate ideas clearly and avoid plagiarism | C | 3 |

BT=Bloom’s Taxonomy, C=Cognitive domain, P=Psychomotor domain, A=Affective domain  

