## **CSC 1103 Fundamentals of Programming**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 1 | **Credits:** | 3 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 1103 | **Course:** | Fundamentals of Programming | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | Computer Science | **Contact Hours:** | 3 hours/Week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | None | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Lab: Fundamentals of | **Lab Course Code:** | CSCL 1103 | | | | |

  
|**Course Objectives** |  
|-|  
| Reference Book | |

**Course Description**  
  
|| |-| 
| This course introduces the fundamental concepts of computer programming using the C language. It s designed for beginners with little or no prior programming experience. The course covers problem- solving techniques, algorithm development, and structured programming concepts. Students will learn the syntax and semantics of C, including variables, data types, operators, control structures, functions, arrays, pointers, strings, and file handling. Emphasis is placed on writing efficient, well-structured, and error-free code through hands-on practice and programming assignments. By the end of thecourse, students will be able to design, implement, debug, and document C programs to solve basic computational problems, providing a solid foundation for advanced courses in programming and computer science. | |

* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-|  
| 1. The C Programming Language, Brian W. Kernighan, Dennis M. Ritchie, 2nd Edition | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---
| 1 | Introduction to Programming |
| 2 | Basics of C Language, Data types, variables, constants |
| 3 | Operators & Expressions |
| 4 | Control Structures – Decision Making |
| 5 | Control Structures – Loops |
| 6 | Problem-Solving with Loops |
| 7 | Functions |
| 8 | Mid Term |
| 9 | Arrays |
| 10 | Strings in C |
| 11 | Pointers in C |
| 12 | Dynamic Memory Allocation |
| 13 | Structures & User-Defined Data Type |
| 14 | File Handling |
| 15 | Review & Project Discussion |

**COURSE LEARNING OUTCOMES (CLOs)**  
| **CLO** | **Description** | **Domain** | **BT Level** |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Understandbasicprogrammingconcepts,operators,andcontrol structures toimplement C programs. | C | 2 |
| 2 | Develop modular programs using functions, arrays, and structures tosolve computational problems | C | 3,6 |
| 3 | Implement file handling, pointers, and dynamic memory allocationtodesignefficient C programs. | C | 3 |

BT=Bloom’s Taxonomy, C=Cognitive domain, P=Psychomotor domain, A=Affective domain  

