## **CSC 1108 Introduction to Computer Science**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 1 | **Credits:** | 2 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 1108 | **Course:** | Introduction to Computer Science | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | GER | **Contact Hours:** | 2 hours/Week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | None | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Lab: | **Lab Course Code:** | CSCL | | | | |

  
|**Course Objectives** |  
|-|  
| 1.| Introduce the basic concepts and terminology of computing and information technology.| 
| 2. | Provide an understanding of computer hardware, software, and operating systems.| 
| 3.|  Develop problem-solving and logical thinking skills using basic programming concepts. | 
| 4. | Equip students with practical skills in productivity software (e.g., word processing, spreadsheets, presentations). | 
|5. | Familiarize students with the web development and databases |
**Course Description**  
 
| |  
|-|  
| This course provides an introduction to the fundamental concepts of computing and information technology. It covers the history and evolution of computers, computer hardware and software, operating systems, data representation, and the role of computing in society. Students will also gain hands-on experience with productivity tools, basic problem-solving techniques, and an introduction to programming. | |
* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-|  
| 1. Introduction to Computers, Peter Norton<br>2. Introduction to Computers, G. M. Long & D. Morley<br>3. Think Python: How to Think Like a Computer Scientist, Allen B. Downey | |

