## **CSC 1107 Applied Physics**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 1 | **Credits:** | 2 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 1107 | **Course:** | Applied Physics | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | GER | **Contact Hours:** | 2 hours/Week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | None | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Lab: Applied Physics | **Lab Course Code:** | Nil | | | | 
**Course Objectives**  
|
| |  
|-|  
| By the end of this course, students will be able to: 1. Understand the basic concepts of electricity, magnetism, and electromagnetism and their applications. 2. Apply fundamental physical laws such as Gauss’s and Faraday’s laws to analyze electric and magnetic fields. 3. Comprehend the principles of wave optics including interference, diffraction, and polarization. Relate physical principles to practical scenarios in computing and electronic systems. | |
  
|**Course Description** |  
|-|  
| This course introduces students to the fundamental principles of electromagnetism and optics with a focus on applications in computing and electrical systems. It covers electric and magnetic fields, Gauss’s and Faraday’s laws, electromagnetic induction, and the behavior of light through reflection, refraction, diffraction, and polarization. Emphasis is placed on problem-solving and conceptual understanding to prepare students for advanced courses in electronics, communication, and computing hardware. | 

* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-|  
| 1. Fundamentals of Physics (Extended), 10th edition, Resnick and Walker<br>2. Narciso Garcia, Arthur Damask, Steven Schwarz., “Physics for Computer Science Students”, Springer Verlag, 1998.<br>3. **SYLLABUS**<br>4. **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---|
| 1 | Electric force and its applications and related problems, conservation of charge, charge quantization |
| 2 | Electric fields due to point charge and lines of force. Ring of charge, Disk of charge 
| 3 | Ring of charge, Disk of charge, A point charge in an electric field, Dipole in a n electric field, The flux of vector field, The flux of electric field |
| 4 | Gauss’ Law, Application of Gauss’ Law, spherically symmetric charge distribution, A charge isolated conductor. |
| 5 | Electric potential energy, Electric potentials |
| 6 | Calculating the potential from the field and related problem Potential due to point and continuous charge distribution |
| 7 | Potential due to dipole, equi-potential surfaces, Calculating the field from the Potential |
| 8 | Mid Term |
| 9 | Ohm’s law and its applications, The Hall effect, The magnetic force on a current |
| 10 | The Biot- Savart law, Line of B, Two parallel conductors, Amperes’ s Law, Solenoid, Toroids, Electric current, Current density, Resistance, Resistivity and conductivity |
| 11 | Faraday’s experiments, Faraday’s Law of Induction, Lenz’s law, Motional emf, Induced electric field, Induced electric fields |
| 12 | The basic equation of electromagnetism, Induced Magnetic field, The displacement Current |
| 13 | Reflection and Refraction of light waves, Total internal reflection, Two source interference, Double Slit interference, related problems |
| 14 | Interference from thin films, Diffraction and the wave theory and their related problems, Single-Slit Diffraction, and related problems |
| 15 | Polarization of electromagnetic waves, Polarizing sheets, related problems. |

**COURSE LEARNING OUTCOMES (CLOs)**  
| **CLO** | **Description** | **Domain** | **BT Level** |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Explain fundamental concepts of electric, magnetic, and electromagnetic fields andtheirinteractions. | C | 2 |
| 2 | Apply Gauss’s Law, Faraday’s Law, and related principles to analyze andsolve basic electromagnetic problems. | C | 3 |
| 3 | Analyze the phenomena of interference, diffraction, and polarizationoflight andrelate them toreal-worldapplications. | C | 4 |

BT=Bloom’s Taxonomy, C=Cognitive domain, P=Psychomotor domain, A=Affective domain  

