## **CSC 2101 Communication & Presentation Skills**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 2 | **Credits:** | 3 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 2101 | **Course:** | Communication & Presentation Skills | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | General Education | **Contact Hours:** | 3 hours/Week | **Pre-Requisite:** | CSC 1102 | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Nil | **Lab Course Code:** | Nil | | | | 
**Course Objectives**  
|
| |  
|-|  
| The course aims to facilitate students in achieving superior public speaking skills to supplement their text book knowledge. During the span of 15 weeks, students will be exposed to delivering speeches and presentations and several speaking exercises to help them set and achieve benchmarks in public speaking. By giving them considerable practical speaking experience, the course helps students speak with confidence and power. | |
**Course Description**  
  
|| |-|  
| The course is aimed at improving English language communication and presentation skills of students. With a multidimensional approach, the course enables the students to practice the use of English in everyday situations, building upon all four skills: listening, speaking, reading and writing. It prepares them to participate in seminars and discussions and make effective presentations, with an awareness of the audience and effective use of verbal and non- verbal communication. The course addresses the basic English language issues faced by the learners, while also aiming to foster inthem, critical skills to develop a concise and clear argument, respond to others’ comments and negotiate their own point of view persuasively. The course uses an interactive, participatory methodology, to engage learners’ interest and boost their confidence to use English in everyday communication in formal and informal contexts. | |

* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-|  
| 1. The Art of Public Speaking by Stephen Lucas (10th Edition) | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---
| 1 | Introduction to communication and presentation skills, Orientation to the course, Importance of communication |
| 2 | Process of communication, Noise and of communication its types mode. |
| 3 | Active Listening, Listening for specific information, Speaking Practice |
| 4 | Types of communication, Barriers in communication, Speaking practice Effective |
| 5 | Seven Cs of Effective communication, general Understanding |
| 6 | Individual presentations with instructors feedback |
| 7 | Individual presentations with instructors feedback |
| 8 | Midterm |
| 9 | Active listening, Listening for specific information (Documentaries) |
| 10 | Argumentative/Persuasive speeches |
| 11 | Importance of reading, Three steps in the reading process, Reading Comprehension |
| 12 | Public speaking, Debating, Role plays, dealing with stage phobia |
| 13 | Individual Presentations with instructors feedback |
| 14 | Individual Presentations with instructors feedback |
| 15 | Individual Presentations |

**COURSE LEARNING OUTCOMES (CLOs)**  
| **CLO** | **Description** | **Domain** | **BT Level** |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Identify and explain the basics of communication, its types, process, and importance. | C | 2 |
| 2 | Developtheskillofactivelisteningandrespondingtoaudience | C | 3 |
| 3 | Prepare and deliver presentations using the principles of effective communication. | C | 3,5 |

BT=Bloom’s Taxonomy, C=Cognitive domain, P=Psychomotor domain, A=Affective domain  

