## **CSC 1207 Digital Logic Design**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 2 | **Credits:** | 2 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 1207 | **Course:** | Digital Logic Design | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | Computer Science | **Contact Hours:** | 2 hours/Week | **Pre-Requisite:** | Nil | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Lab Digital Logic Design | **Lab Course Code:** | CSCL 2103 | | | | |

  
|**Course Objectives** |  
|-|  
| To impart knowledge about digital logic and to gain the ability to design various digital circuits. Through the basic understanding of Boolean algebra and number systems it introduces the student to the fundamentals of combinational logic design and then to sequential circuits (both synchronous and asynchronous). Memory systems are also covered. Finally, the student is introduced to Register Transfer Logic design and the structured implementation of controllers and micro programmed computers. |
**Course Description**   

| |  
|-|  
| This course covers the basics of digital logic circuits and design. Through the basic understanding of Boolean algebra and number systems it introduces the student to the fundamentals of combinational logic design and then to sequential circuits (both synchronous and asynchronous). Memory systems are also covered. Finally, the student is introduced to Register Transfer Logic design and the structured implementation of controllers and micro programmed computers. | |
* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-|  
| 1. Floyd T.L, DigitalFundamentals,10/e, Pearson Education, 2011<br>2. Mano M.M, Digital Design 5th Edition, Pearson Education<br>3. Fundamentals of Digital Logic with Verilog design, Stephen Brown, 2nd Edition | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** 
|---|---|
| 1 | Introduction to digital system and different number systems, Binary arithmetic (addition, subtraction etc.) |
| 2 | Decimal to Binary Conversion, Binary to Decimal Conversion, Decimal to Octal Conversion, Octal to Decimal Conversion, Decimal to Hexadecimal Conversion, Hexadecimal to Decimal Conversion, Binary to Octal Conversion, Octal to Binary Conversion, |
| 3 | Duality and Truth tables, Standard forms of Boolean functions, Methods to obtain lists of SOP and POS forms of Boolean functions. |
| 4 | Effects of minimization, Boolean Minimization techniques, Algebraic method, Karnaugh map (K map) method, Don’t care conditions. Quinn Mc- Cluskey method |
| 5 | Introduction to logic Gates, Derivation of Boolean expressions from logic circuits, Derivation of logic levels from logic circuits, Designing of logic circuits from Boolean expressions. |
| 6 | Introduction to Universal logic gates, Applications of logic gates, Introduction to logic conventions, Integrated circuits (ICs). |
| 7 | Introduction to combinational logic circuits, Procedure of designing combinational logic circuits, designing of custom built combinational logic circuits, Binary adders, and Parallel binary adders. Binary Arithmetic circuits: Ripple carry versus look ahead carry adders (Half adders, full adders), Binary Subtractor, Binary comparators. |
| 8 | Mid Term |
| 9 | Decoders (DECs), Encoders (ENCs),Multiplexers (MUXs), De-Multiplexers (De- MUXs), Error detecting circuits |
| 10 | Introduction to sequential logic circuits, Comparison of sequential and combinational logic circuits |
| 11 | Synchronous sequential logic circuits, Asynchronous sequential logic circuits. |
| 12 | Digital timing signal characteristics, Memory devices (Flip-Flops), Types of flip- flops, Characteristic and Excitation tables, Conversions among flip-flops, Memory designing with flip-flops. Introduction to register memory, Basic functions of shift registers, Types of shift registers, Shift register counters, Applications of shift registers. |
| 13 | Introduction to Finite State Machines, Moore Machines, Mealy Machines, Implementation of Finite State Machines. Asynchronous and Synchronous Mode Counters, Randomly Counting Circuits. |
| 14 | Memory Elements, Read and Write, Addressing, ROMs, PROMs and EPROMs, RAMs |
| 15 | Sequential Programmable Logic Devices - PAL, PLA, FPGA (Introduction and basic concepts only) Introduction to VHDL, Implementation of AND, OR, half adder and full adder. |

**COURSE LEARNING OUTCOMES (CLOs)**  
| **CLO** | **Description** | **Domain** | **BT Level** |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Explain number systems, binary arithmetic, Boolean algebra, and logic gates,andanalyzetruthtablesandstandardformsofBooleanfunctions. | C | 2,4 |
| 2 | Apply Boolean minimization techniques (Algebraic, K-map, Quine- McCluskey)todesignandsimplifylogiccircuits | C | 3,5 |
| 3 | Design combinational and sequential logic circuits, including adders, subtractors,multiplexers,decoders,flip-flops,registers,andcounters. | C | 6 |
| 4 | Demonstrateknowledgeofdigitalmemorydevices,programmablelogic devices (PAL, PLA, FPGA), and VHDL basics, and analyze their applicationsindigitalsystems. | C | 2,4 |

BT=Bloom’s Taxonomy, C=Cognitive domain, P=Psychomotor domain, A=Affective domain  

