## **CSC 1209 Humanities**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 1 | **Credits:** | 2 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 1209 | **Course:** | Humanities | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | GER | **Contact Hours:** | 2 hours/Week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | None | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Nil | **Lab Course Code:** | Nil | | | | |

  
|**Course Objectives** |  
|-|  
| Reference Books: | 
**Course Description**|
  
| |  
|-| 
| This course provides an introduction to the study of human culture, ethics, philosophy, and social sciences. It explores historical, cultural, and ethical perspectives that influence modern societies and technological advancements. Special emphasis is placed on ethical considerations in AI and computing, ensuring students understand their professional and social responsibilities. | |
**Text/Reference Books :** 
  
|| |-|  
| 1. Yuval Noah Harari – Sapiens: A Brief History of Humankind (Harper, 2015)<br>2. Charles Bressler – Literary Criticism: An Introduction to Theory and Practice (Pearson, 2017)<br>3. John Rawls – A Theory of Justice (Harvard University Press, 2005)<br>4. Develop a broad understanding of human culture, ethics, and philosophy.<br>5. Explore historical and contemporary perspectives on societal development.<br>6. Analyze the relationship between technology, ethics, and society.<br>7. Strengthen critical thinking and communication skills in social discourse.<br>8. Foster a sense of professional andethical responsibility in AI applications.<br>9. Henry M. Sayre – Discovering the Humanities (Pearson, 2019)<br>10. Michael Sandel – Justice: What's the Right Thing to Do? (Farrar, Straus and Giroux, 2010)<br>11. Russ Shafer-Landau – The Fundamentals of Ethics (Oxford University Press, 2021) | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---|
| 1 | Introduction to Humanities: Definition, Scope, and Importance |
| 2 | History of Civilization: Ancient to Modern Societies |
