## **CSC 1206 Probability and Statistics**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 2 | **Credits:** | 3 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 1206 | **Course:** | Probability and Statistics | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | Mathematics & Science | **Contact Hours:** | 3 hours/Week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | None | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Nil | **Lab Course Code:** | Nil | | | | |

  
|**Course Objectives** |  
|-|  
| After completing this course student should be able to demonstrate understanding of basic probability axioms and rules and the moments of discrete and continuous random variables as well as be familiar with common named discrete and continuous random variables and how to derive the probability density function of transformations of random variables and use these techniques to generate data from various distributions. Students will also be able to understand how to calculate probabilities, and derive the marginal and conditional distributions of bivariate random variables. | 

  
|**Course Description** |  
|-|  
| A course “Statistics and Probability Theory” emphasizes the probabilistic foundations required to understand probability models and statistical methods. Topics covered will include the introduction to statistical methods (understanding data and its importance, data classification, tabulation, graphical representation), Central Tendencies, dispersion. Probability axioms, basic combinatory, discrete and continuous random variables, probability distributions, mathematical expectation, common families of probability distributions. Introduction to correlation and regression. | 

* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-|  
| 1. Probability & Statistics for Engineers & Scientists, Ronald E. Walpole; Raymond H. Myers;<br>2. Sharon L. Myers; Keying E. Ye 9th Edition Pearson, (2016) ISBN-13: 978-0134115856<br>3. Elementary Statistics: A Step by Step Approach, Allan G. Bluman. 8th Edition, (2012)<br>4. ISBN- 978-0-07-338610-2 | |

**SYLLABUS** 
| **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---|
| 1 | Introduction to Statistics and Data Analysis, Data Collection Methods, Populations, Samples, Sampling Procedures, Types of Statistical Studies |
| 2 | Measurement Scales, Random and Non-random Sampling, Tabulation, Presentation of data, Frequency Distribution, |
| 3 | Measures of central tendency (Arithmetic mean, Harmonic mean, and Geometric mean), Mode, Median, Quartiles, Deciles, Percentiles of ungrouped Data |
| 4 | Using Grouped Data to estimate Mean, Mode, Median, Quartiles, Deciles, and Percentiles. |
| 5 | Graphical representation of Data using Different Graphs and GAts |
| 6 | Measure of Dispersion and their types, Skewness, coefficient of Variation- Consistency and relative comparison |
| 7 | Introduction to Simple Regression Model, Correlation coefficient and its interpretation to interpret relationships and modeling data. |
| 8 | Mid Terms |
| 9 | Introduction to set theory, Probability, Sample Space, Events, Counting Sample Points, Probability of an Event, Additive Rules. Conditional Probability, Independence, and the Product Rule, Bayes’ Rule. Application of probability in modeling of uncertainty. |
| 10 | Random Variables and Probability Distributions. Mathematical Expectation: Mean of a Random Variable, Variance and Covariance of Random Variables, (Discrete and continuous). |
| 11 | Probability distributions (classification based on types of variable). |
| 12 | Bernoulli, Binomial, Poisson, Negative Binomial and geometric probability distributions. |
| 13 | Properties and their interpretations, Moment Generating Functions. |
| 14 | Normal distribution, Exponential distribution, Gamma distribution and their properties. |
| 15 | Application to the real life problems of Normal distribution, Exponential distribution and Gamma distribution |

**COURSE LEARNING OUTCOMES (CLOs)**  
| **CLO** | **Description** | **Domain** | **BT Level** |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Introduction to the Statistical thinking, manipulating the data and organization specific emphasis to the computer sciences field like datamining. | C | 2 |
| 2 | MeasureofCentralTendency,LocationandmeasureofDispersion. Definingtheaveragesandpossibledispersioninthedata.Impactof thelocationofdataonstatisticalanalysis. | C | 2,3,4 |
| 3 | Understanduncertainty,modeluncertainsituationsandfindprecise estimatesusingprobabilityanditsLaws | C | 2,3 |
| 4 | Understand Random Variables, discrete and continuous probability distributions,andtheirproperties. | C | 2,3 |
| 5 | Applications of Continuous probability distribution in real life situations. | C | 2,3 |

