## **CSC 1201 Discrete Mathematical Structures**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 3 | **Credits:** | 3 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 1201 | **Course:** | Discrete Mathematical Structures | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | Computer Science | **Contact Hours:** | 3 hours/week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | None | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Nil | **Lab Course Code:** | Nil | | | | 
**Course Objectives**  
|
| |  
|-|  
| Introduces the foundations of discrete mathematics as they apply to Computer Science, focusing on providing a solid theoretical foundation for further work. Further, this course aims to develop understanding and appreciation of the finite nature inherent in most Computer Science problems and structures through study of combinatorial reasoning, abstract algebra, iterative procedures, predicate calculus, tree and graph structures | |
**Course Description**  
  
|| |-|  
| This course introduces fundamental mathematical structures necessary for the development of program logic. It covers logic: propositional logic; negation disjunction and conjunction; implication and equivalence; truth tables; predicates; quantifiers; Set theory: inductive definition of sets and proof by induction; Relations: representation of relations by graphs; properties of relations, equivalence relations Functions: mappings, injection and surjection, composition of functions; inverse functions; Recursive function theory; Elementary combinatoric; counting techniques; recurrence relation;generating functions. Graph Theory: elements of graph theory, Planar Graphs, Graph Coloring, Euler graph, Hamiltonian path, trees, spanning tree, minimal spanning tree and their applications. | |

* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-|  
| 1. Discrete Mathematics and Its Applications, Kenneth H.Rosen, 6th Edition, McGraw Hill. | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---
| 1 | Introduction to discrete structures, definitions, application in real world, important areas to cover. Logic definition, proposition (logic and variables), disjunction, conjunction, negations, conditional statements, bi-conditional statements |
| 2 | Truth tables for compound proposition, bit operations, translating English sentence into compound propositions, logical equivalences, Tautologies and contradiction, useful logical equivalences, Laws of logic, Notions of implication (converse, inverse, contrapositive) |
| 3 | Predicate and Quantifiers, Valid and Invalid argument form |
| 4 | Sets, representations of set, empty set, equal set, Venn diagram, subset, Power set, cardinality, ordered n-tuples, Cartesian product, set operations (union, intersection, complement), Computer representation of set |
| 5 | Relations, relations on a set, properties of relation, reflexive, symmetric relations, antisymmetric, transitive relations |
| 6 | Combining relations, Composition of relations, Matrix representation of relations, representing relations using digraphs, equivalence relation |
| 7 | Functions, domain, codomain, range, one-to-one functions, Onto function |
| 8 | Mid Term |
| 9 | Sequence, Series, Recursion, Composition of functions, one to one correspondence, equality of functions, identity function, inverse function |
| 10 | Mathematical induction, structural induction, strong and weak induction, Mathematical induction for divisibility |
| 11 | Combination, Permutations, Combinations, K-Combinations |
| 12 | Tree diagram, Inclusion-exclusion principle, Pigeonhole Principle |
| 13 | Graphs, Paths and circuits, Matrix representation, Isomorphism |
| 14 | Planar graphs, Trees, Spanning Trees |
| 15 | Boolean Algebra |

**COURSE LEARNING OUTCOMES (CLOs)**  
| **CLO** | **Description** | **Domain** | **BT Level** |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Understand the key concepts of discrete structures such as proposition,sets,permutations,relations,graphsandtree | C | 2 |
| 2 | Apply formal logic proofs and/or informal logical reasoning to real world problems by comprehending and constructing mathematical arguments | C | 2 |
| 3 | Performcombinatoryanalysistosolvecountingproblems | C | 3 |
| 4 | Apply the knowledge and skills obtained to investigate discrete mathematicalproblemsandsolveotherproblemsincomputing | C | 3 |

BT=Bloom’s Taxonomy, C=Cognitive domain, P=Psychomotor domain, A=Affective domain  

