## **CSC 2102 Data Structures and Algorithms**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 3 | **Credits:** |  |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 2102 | **Course:** | Data Structure and Algorithms | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | Computer Science | **Contact Hours:** | 3 hours/week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | CSC 1208, CSCL 1208 | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Lab: Data Structure and | **Lab Course Code:** | CSCL 2102 | | | | 
**Course Objectives**  
|
| |  
|-|  
| The purpose of this course is to provide the students with solid foundations in the basic concepts of programming data structures and algorithms. The main objective of the course is to teach the students how to select and design data structures and algorithms that are appropriate for problems that they might encounter. This course is also about showing the  |
**Coucorrectness of algorithms and studying their computational complexities. |rse Description**  
| |  
|-|  
| Introduction to Data Structures and Algorithms, Arrays, Linked Lists, Stacks, Queues, analysis of algorithms, trees, binary search trees, hash tables, graphs, graph traversals, graph algorithms, Sorting. Introduction to Data Structures and Algorithms, Arrays, Linked Lists, Stacks, Queues, analysis of algorithms, trees, binary search trees, hash tables, graphs, graph traversals, graph algorithms, Sorting. | |
* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-|  
| 1. Data Structures and Algorithms in Java, fifth edition Michael T. Goodrich and Roberto Tamassia<br>2. John Wiley & Sons Inc., 2010.<br>3. Data Structures and Algorithms in Java, 2nd Edition, Robert Lafore, Sams Publishing, 2003. | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** 
|---|---|
| 1 | Data structures, importance and types. Abstract Data Types. Time and Space Complexity (Big O). |
| 2 | Static vs Dynamic data structures, Arrays, Structures. Need for list. Implementing sequential lists using arrays. List Operations. |
| 3 | Singly, Doubly & Circular linked Lists and various operations on them. |
| 4 | Stacks and their importance. Array Representation. Stack Operations. Infix, Postfix and Prefix Expressions, Infix to postfix conversion Algorithm, Evaluating postfix expression. |
| 5 | Recursion: Function Call and Recursion Implementation. Recursion, Non-tail Recursion, Indirect Recursion, Nested Recursion, Backtracking. |
| 6 | Queues. Operations. Circular, Double Ended and Priority Queues. Applications of Queues. |
| 7 | Basic concepts of rooted Tree, Binary tree and tree traversal algorithms. |
| 8 | Binary Search trees and its various operations, linear search |
| 9 | AVL Trees. Insertion, Deletion and Rotations. |
| 10 | Building Max and Min Heaps. Deletion in a heap. Heap Sort. |
| 11 | Graph and the representations. Adjacency Matrix. Adjacency List. Directed and Undirected Graphs. Application area of graph. Traversal techniques. Minimum spanning trees. |
| 12 | Shortest path algorithm: Dijkstra’s Algorithm, Bellman ford algorithm |
| 13 | Hash functions and tables. Strategies for avoiding and resolving collisions. |
| 14 | Binary search and its time complexity. |
| 15 | Bubble, Selection, Insertion, Merge and Quick Sorts. |

**COURSE LEARNING OUTCOMES (CLOs)**  
| **CLO** | **Description** | **Domain** | **BT Level** |
|---|---|---|---|
