**CSCL 3105 Lab Computer Organization and ## Assembly Language**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 3 | **Credits:** | 1 |
| **Course Code:** | CSCL 3105 | **Course:** | Lab: Computer Organization and Assembly Language | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | Computer Science | **Contact Hours:** | 3 hours/Week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | CSC 1207, CSCL 1207 | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Nil | **Lab Course Code:** | Nil | | | | 
**Course Objectives**  
|
| |  
|-|  
| The main objective of this course is to introduce the organization of computer systems and usage of assembly language for optimization and control. Emphasis should be given to expose the low- level logic employed for problem solving while using assembly language as a tool. At the end of the course the students should be capable of writing moderately complex assembly language subroutines and interfacing them to any high level language. | |
  
|**Course Description** |  
|-|  
| This course covers the fundamental concepts of Computer organization and Assembly language. The tops include Octal and hexadecimal number systems, ASCII codes, Assembly language programming. Instruction formats and types, memory and I/O instructions, arithmetic instructions, addressing modes, stack operations, procedures, conditional processing, shift and rotate instructions along with Multiplication and division. Advance procedures and interrupt handling. Practice of assembly language programming. | 

* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-|  
| 1. Assembly Language for x86 Processors, 6th Edition, Kip R. Irvine, Prentice Hall, 2010 | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---
| 1 | Introduction to Assembly Language, Microprocessors, Architecture (Intel 8086), How program execute? |
| 2 | MASM, NASM, Emulator (in detail) |
| 3 | Data Registers: AX, BX, CX, DX, Instructions: MOV, ADD, SUB, INC, DEC, Program structure, Basic I/O Instructions |
| 4 | Number Systems, Segment Offset Addressing Scheme, Segment Registers: CS, DS, SS, Memory Segment |
| 5 | Binary I/O, Hexadecimal I/O, Conversions, Count number of zeros & ones in a character |
| 6 | Variables, Data Declaration Directives: DB, DW, DD, DQ, DT, Memory to Memory Operation Issue, Control Registers: OF, DF, SF, ZF, AF, PF, CF |
| 7 | Flow Control, JMP Instruction, Unconditional Jumps, Conditional Jumps |
| 8 | Midterm Examination |
| 9 | Single Flag Jumps, LOOP Instruction |
| 10 | Logical Instructions, NOT, AND, OR, XOR, CMP Instruction, TEST Instruction |
| 11 | Shift Instructions, Rotate Instructions, MUL Instruction, DIV Instruction, Decimal Input and Output Procedures |
| 12 | Arrays, Addressing Modes, Index Registers: SI, DI |
| 13 | Stack, Pointer Registers: IP, SP, BP, Procedures |
| 14 | Interrupts (10h 00-0A, 21h) |
| 15 | Revision and practice / project 111 CSC3106 HCI and Computer Graphics COURSE INFORMATION SHEET PROGRAMME: BSCS/BSSE/BSAI DEGREE: BSCS COURSE: HCI and Computer Graphics SEMESTER: III CREDITS: 2 COURSE CODE: CSC1111 COURSE TYPE: Domain Core COURSE AREA/DOMAIN: Core CONTACT HOURS: 2 hours/Week CORRESPONDING LAB COURSE CODE(IFANY): CSCL 3106 LAB COURSE NAME: Lab: HCI and Computer Graphics COURSE OBJECTIVES: This course will enable the student to understand fundamental HCI principles and apply usability heuristics in interface design, analyze cognitive and perceptual models that influence user interaction, apply 2D and 3D graphics techniques, including color theory, visual hierarchy, and rendering and evaluate and improve user interfaces through prototyping and usability testing. COURSE DESCRIPTION: This course provides an introduction to Human-Computer Interaction (HCI) and Computer Graphics, focusing on designing and evaluating user-friendly interfaces and understanding graphical representations in computing. The HCI component explores user-centered design principles, usability heuristics, cognitive models, and accessibility considerations. The Computer Graphics component introduces 2D and 3D graphics, rendering techniques, color theory, and visual hierarchy, emphasizing their role in interface design and interaction. SYLLABUS: |

