## **CSC 3101 Computer Architecture**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 4 | **Credits:** | 3 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 2206 | **Course:** | Linear Algebra | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | Maths | **Contact Hours:** | 3 hours/Week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | None | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Nil | **Lab Course Code:** | Nil | | | | |

**Course Objectives**  
  
|| |-|  
| Programme: CS/SE/AI Degree: BS Course: Linear Algebra Semester: 4 Credits:3 Course Code: CSC 2206 Course Type: Core Course Area/Domain: Maths Contact Hours: 3 hours/Week. Corresponding Lab Course Code (If any): Nil Lab Course Name: Nil Course Pre-Requisite: None This course introduces students to the fundamental concepts and design principles of modern computer systems. The course covers the organization and structure of computer hardware, instruction set architecture (ISA), CPU design, memory hierarchy, input/output systems, and emerging trends in multicore and parallel architectures. Students willgain a strong understanding of how hardware components interact to execute programs efficiently, as well as practical insights into modern processor architectures, including RISC-V. The course emphasizes both theoretical knowledge and hands-on analysis of computer architectures, preparing students for advanced topics in system design, optimization, and performance evaluation. By the end of this course, students will be able to: 1. Understand foundational concepts in computer architecture and organization, including the Von Neumann model, data representation, and number systems. 2. Explain instruction set architecture (ISA) concepts, instruction formats, addressing modes, and basic assembly programming. 3. Analyze CPU components such as ALU, registers, buses, and understand the role of the control unit (hardwired and microprogrammed). 4. Describe pipelining techniques and identify pipeline hazards, including solutions like forwarding and branch prediction. 5. Explain memory hierarchy concepts, cache mapping, replacement policies, and virtual memory organization. 126 | |

  
|**Course Description** |  
|-|  
|  | |

* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-| 
|   | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---
| 1 | Introduction to Computer Architecture & Organization |
| 2 | Von Neumann Model, Number Systems, Data Representation |
| 3 | Instruction Set Architecture (ISA) Concepts |
| 4 | Instruction Formats, Addressing Modes, Basic Assembly |
| 5 | CPU Datapath Components (ALU, Registers, Buses) |
| 6 | Control Unit — Hardwired & Microprogrammed |
| 7 | Introduction to Pipelining |
| 8 | Pipeline Hazards, Forwarding, Prediction Techniques |
| 9 | Memory Hierarchy Basics |
| 10 | Cache Mapping, Replacement Policies, Virtual Memory |
| 11 | I/O Systems, Interrupts |
| 12 | DMA, Bus Architecture, Peripheral Communication |
| 13 | Flynn’s Taxonomy & Parallel Processing |
| 14 | Multicore, GPU Architecture, SIMD/MIMD |
| 15 | RISC-V Basics, Modern Architectures & Trends |

**COURSE LEARNING OUTCOMES (CLOs)**  
| **CLO** | **Description** | **Domain** | **BT Level** |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Explain the key components and operational principles of computer systems including ISA, datapath, control, memory hierarchy,andI/Osubsystems. | C | 2 |
| 2 | Analyze processor and memory performance using CPI, pipeline behavior,andcacheefficiencymetrics | C | 4 |
| 3 | Design and evaluate simple processor datapaths, pipelined structures, or memory subsystems based on given design requirements | C | 5 |
| 4 | Use modern architectural tools or simulators to model system behaviorandeffectivelydocumentorpresentresults | C | 3 |

