**Course Objectives**  
  
|| |-|  
| Programme: CS/SE/AI Degree: BS Course: Linear Algebra Semester: 4 Credits:3 Course Code: CSC 2206 Course Type: Core Course Area/Domain: Maths Contact Hours: 3 hours/Week. Corresponding Lab Course Code (If any): Nil Lab Course Name: Nil Course Pre-Requisite: None The objective of the course is to provide a rigorous approach towards the solutions of linear models, which involves more than one variable. The techniques discussed in this course can be implemented on a wide range of applications from physical world. The matrix algebra will be helpful in performing and understanding of matrix computationson a machine. The eigenvalues, eigenvectors, inner product spaces, orthogonality are useful concepts for the analysis of dynamical systems. This course has been designed to acquire a good understanding of the concepts and methods of linear algebra, to develop the ability to solve problems using the techniques of linear algebra using Eigen values and Eigen vectors. | |

  
|**Course Description** |  
|-|  
|  | |

* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-| 
| 1. Elementary Linear Algebra by Howard Anton<br>2. Linear Algebra and its Applications by Gibert Strang | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---
| 1 | Applications of Linear Algebra in Computer Science, Matrices and Determinants (i) Types of matrices (ii) Matrix multiplication (iii) Determinants |
| 2 | Systems of Linear Equations (i) Types of linear systems of equations, homogeneous and non-homogeneous linear systems of equations. (ii) Possible solutions for homogeneous linear systems of equations. (iii) Possible solutions for non-homogeneous linear systems of equations. (iv) Solution of linear systems of equations by Gaussian elimination method and Gauss-Jordan elimination method. |
| 3 | Systems of Linear Equations (i) Rank, invertibility and row echelon form of matrices. (ii) Inverse of matrix by Gauss-Jordan method. |
| 4 | Vector Spaces (i) Euclidean vector spaces. (ii) Matrix space. (iii) Polynomial space. (iv) Continuous function space. (v) Sub-spaces of a vector space. |
| 5 | Vector Spaces (i) Linear combination in a vector space. (ii) Spanning set of a vector space. |
| 6 | Linear Dependence Conditions for linear dependence of vectors. |
| 7 | Linear Independence Conditions for linear independence of vectors. |
| 8 | Midterm Exam Midterm Exam |
| 9 | Bases Method for finding the basis and dimension of a vector space. |
| 10 | Inner Product Space (i) Euclidean inner product space. (ii) Inner product on matrix space. (iii) Inner product on polynomial space. (iv) Inner product on continuous function space. |
| 11 | Inner Product Space (i) Conversion of arbitrary basis into orthogonal basis by Gram-Schmidt process. (ii)Conversion of orthogonal basis into orthonormal basis. |
| 12 | Eigen Values and Eigen Vectors Eigen values, Eigen vectors and characteristic equations. |
| 13 | Eigen Values and Eigen Vectors (i) Diagonalization (ii) Orthogonal Diagonalization |
| 14 | Quadratic Form (i) Converting a quadratic form to a diagonal form. (ii) Reducing a quadratic form to a sum of squares. (iii) Rotation and translation of conics. |
| 15 | Linear Transformation Linear transformation in finite dimensional vector spaces. |

