## **CSC 3107 Operating Systems**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 5 | **Credits:** | 2 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 3107 | **Course:** | Operating Systems | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | Computer Science | **Contact Hours:** | 2 hours/Week | **Pre-Requisite:** | None | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Lab Operating Systems | **Lab Course Code:** | CSCL 2205 | | | | |

  
|**Course Objectives** |  
|-|  
| Programme: CS/SE/AI Degree: BS Course: Operating Systems Semester: 5 Credits: 2 Course Code: CSC 3107 Course Type: Core Course Area/Domain: Computer Science Contact Hours: 2 hours/Week Corresponding Lab Course Code (If any): CSCL 2205 Lab Course Name: Lab Operating Systems Course Pre-Requisite: None The purpose of this course is to provide an understanding of operating systems to students so they will be able to understand the terminology surrounding and describing operating systems. | 

  
|**Course Description** |  
|-|  
|  | |

**Text/Reference Books :** 
  
|| |-| 
| 1. Students will become familiar with the kinds of abstractions provided by general purpose<br>2. operating systems that facilitate the development of user applications. Also they will become<br>3. familiar with the typical internal policies and mechanisms implemented by operating systems<br>4. and how they impact system performance.<br>5. This course is an introduction to the theory and practice behind modern operating systems.<br>6. Topics will include what an operating system does, system calls and interfaces, processes,<br>7. concurrent programming, resource scheduling and management, virtualmemory, deadlocks and<br>8. security.<br>9. Operating systems concepts, Abraham Silberschatz, 9th Edition, Wiley,2012.<br>10. Modern Operating Systems, Andrew S. Tanenbaum, 4th Edition, Pearson,2014. | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---|
| 1 | Operating system basics, system calls |
| 2 | Process Concept and scheduling, process scheduling algorithms |
| 3 | Multiprocessor scheduling |
| 4 | Inter-Process Communication |
| 5 | Multithreaded programming, multithreading models, threading issues, thread scheduling |
| 6 | Synchronization, critical section |
| 7 | Synchronization hardware, Synchronization problems, Deadlocks, detecting and recovering from deadlocks |
| 8 | Mid Term |
| 9 | Memory Management, swapping, contiguous memory allocation. |
| 10 | Segmentation & Paging, virtual memory management, demand paging, thrashing |
| 11 | Memory-mapped files, file systems, file concept |
| 12 | Directory and disk structure, directory implementation |
| 13 | Free space management, disk structure, directory implementation |
| 14 | Virtual Machines |
| 15 | System Protection, Operating system security TEXT/REFERENCE BOOKS Operating systems concepts, Abraham Silberschatz, 9th Edition, Wiley,2012. Modern Operating Systems, Andrew S. Tanenbaum, 4th Edition, Pearson,2014. |

