**CSC 3108 Advance Database Management Systems (2,## 0)**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 5 | **Credits:** | 2 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 3108 | **Course:** | Advanced Database Management Systems | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | Computer | **Contact Hours:** | 2 hours/Week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | CLO | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Lab: Advanced Database | **Lab Course Code:** | CSCL 3108 | | | | |

  
|**Course Objectives** |  
|-|  
|  | |

  
|**Course Description** |  
|-| 
|  | |

* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-| 
|   | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---
| 1 | Introduction to Advanced DBMS Concepts – Overview, evolution, and scope of advanced databases. |
| 2 | Review of SQL and Relational Database Concepts – Normalization, relational algebra, constraints, and advanced querying basics. |
| 3 | Advanced SQL: Stored Procedures – Syntax, parameters, control structures, and use cases. |
| 4 | Advanced SQL: Functions and Triggers – Creating functions, triggers for enforcing business rules, examples, and best practices. |
| 5 | Advanced SQL: Cursors and Dynamic SQL – Cursor types, fetching, iteration, and dynamic query execution. |
| 6 | Transaction Management – ACID properties, transaction states, schedules, and serializability. |
| 7 | Concurrency Control Mechanisms – Lock-based protocols, timestamp ordering, optimistic concurrency control, and deadlock handling. |
| 8 | Recovery Techniques – Checkpointing, log-based recovery, deferred and immediate update strategies. |
| 9 | Distributed Database Concepts – Overview, architectures, fragmentation, replication, and allocation strategies. |
| 10 | Distributed Query Processing – Query decomposition, optimization, and execution in distributed environments. |
| 11 | Replication and Consistency Models – Synchronous/asynchronous replication, eventual consistency, and conflict resolution. |
| 12 | Data Warehousing Concepts – OLAP vs OLTP, ETL processes, star and snowflake schemas, and data marts. |
| 13 | Emerging Database Technologies – NoSQL systems: key-value, document, column- family, graph databases. |
| 14 | Big Data Platforms – Hadoop ecosystem, Spark SQL, distributed storage, and analytics frameworks. |
| 15 | Case Studies, Project Presentations, and Revision – Real-world applications, integrating advanced SQL, distributed DB, and big data solutions. |

**COURSE LEARNING OUTCOMES (CLOs)**  
| **CLO** | **Description** | **Domain** | **BT Level** |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | ApplyadvancedSQL features includingstored procedures,functions,triggers,andcursors for complexdatabase operations. | C | 3 |
| 2 | Analyze transactionprocessing,concurrency control mechanisms,anddatabase recovery techniques inmulti-userenvironments. | C | 4 |
| 3 | Evaluate distributeddatabase architectures, replicationstrategies,anddata warehousing principles forenterprise applications. | C | 5 |
| 4 | Designandimplement solutions usingemerging database technologies includingNoSQL systems andbigdata platforms. | C | 6 |

