## **CSC 3206 Artificial Intelligence**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 3 | **Credits:** | 2 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 3206 | **Course:** | Artificial Intelligence | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | Computer Science | **Contact Hours:** | 2 hours/Week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | CSC 1208, CSCL 1208 | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Lab Artificial Intelligence | **Lab Course Code:** | CSCL | | | | 
**Course Objectives**  
|
| |  
|-|  
| The objective of the course is to present an overview of artificial intelligence (AI) principles and approaches. Develop a basic understanding of the building blocks of AI as presented in terms of intelligent agents: Search, Knowledge representation, inference, logic, and learning. Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach, Russell, S., &Norvig, P.,  |
**Course Description**  
(2013), Prentice Hall. Prolog || |  
|-|  
| Artificial Neural Network includes subject of the McCulloch-Pitts Model, activation functions, loss and cost functions, feed-forward and feed-back network structures, Single Layer perceptron’s, Multi-Layer perceptron’s, Radial-based function networks, weighted networks, perceptron learning algorithms, strategies for avoiding overfitting and underfitting, accelerating convergence and recurrent networks. | |
* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-|  
| 1. Programming for Artificial Intelligence, Bratko, I., (2012), Addison-Wesley.<br>2. Machine Learning, Mitchell, T., (1997), McGraw-Hill | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** 
|---|---|
| 1 | Overview of AI Problems; Intelligent Behavior: Turing Test, Formal Definitions for Artificial Intelligence, History and Evolution of Artificial Intelligence |
| 2 | Intelligent agents and agents environments, Single versus Multi agent. |
| 3 | Knowledge based systems, Nature of Agents: Autonomous versus Semi- autonomous, Reflexive, Goal-based and Utility-based. |
| 4 | Tree and Graph, Search Strategies, DFS, BFS, Heuristically Informed Searches, |
| 5 | Hill Climbing, A* Search. Adversarial Search, time and space complexity |
| 6 | Problem Solving, Problem Representation, Components of Problem Solving, The Two– One Problem. |
| 7 | Propositional and Predicate Logic. Pros and Cons of propositional logic, First Order Logic. |
| 8 | Midterm Exam |
| 9 | Syntax and Semantics of FOL, Using FOL, Atomic/Complex Sentences, Rules of Inference. |
| 10 | Proof, Resolution Inference Rule, Resolution Proof. |
| 11 | Forward chaining algorithm, backward chaining algorithm. |
| 12 | Classification, Inductive Learning, Simple Statistical Based Learning, |
| 13 | Machine Learning: Decision Tree |
| 14 | Neural Networks, Artificial Neural Networks, Single Layer Feed Forward neural net. |
| 15 | Multilayer feed forward neural networks, multilayer back propagation neural networks |

