## **CSCL 3206 Lab Artificial Intelligence**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 3 | **Credits:** | 1 |
| **Course Code:** | CSCL 3206 | **Course:** | Lab Artificial Intelligence | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | Computer Science | **Contact Hours:** | 3 hours/Week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | CSC 1208, CSCL 1208 | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Nil | **Lab Course Code:** | Nil | | | | |

**Course Objectives**  
  
|| |-|  
| The objective of the course is to present an overview of artificial intelligence (AI) principles and approaches. Develop a basic understanding of the building blocks of AI as presented in terms of intelligent agents: Search, Knowledge representation, inference, logic, and learning. This course gives a broad overview of the fundamental theories and techniques of Artificial Intelligence. Major topics covered in the lectures include: Overview of AI Problems; Intelligent Behavior: Turing Test, Rationale versus Non-rationale Reasoning; Problem Characteristics: Fully versus Partially Observable,Single versus Multi agent; Intelligent Agents: reactive, deliberative, goal-driven, utility-driven, and learning agents; Uninformed Search: Depth First, Breadth First, Depth First with Iterative Deepening; Informed Search: Hill climbing, A*- Search and their Time and Space Complexity, Local Search, Genetic Algorithm; Game Playing: Min- max, Evaluation functions, Alpha-beta pruning; Propositional and Predicate Logic; Resolution and Theorem Proving; Forward and Backward Chaining; Machine Learning: Introduction, Supervised learning: Inductive networks. learning, Decision tree, Artificial neural Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach, Russell, S., & Norvig, P., (2013), Prentice Hall. | |

  
|**Course Description** |  
|-|  
|  | |

* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-| 
| 1. Prolog Programming for Artificial Intelligence, Bratko, I., (2012), Addison-Wesley.<br>2. Machine Learning, Mitchell, T., (1997), McGraw-Hill | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** 
|---|---|
| 1 | Python Introduction – Data Structures and Loops |
| 2 | Python Introduction – Functions, Tuples, Sets and Dictionaries |
| 3 | Searching – Uninformed searches -Breadth First Search |
| 4 | Uninformed searches -Depth First Search |
| 5 | Heuristic Search – Greedy Best search, A* Search |
| 6 | Genetic Algorithms |
| 7 | Prolog Introduction |
| 8 | Complex Knowledgebase in Prolog |
| 9 | Expert Systems in Prolog, FWD BWD |
| 10 | Introduction to Matlab |
| 11 | Linear Regression |
| 12 | Linear Classification – Decision Tree |
| 13 | Regression and Classification using K nearest Neighbors |
| 14 | Classification using Single layer Artificial Neural Networks |
| 15 | Classification using Multi-layer Artificial Neural Networks |

