## **CSC 4109 Professional Practices**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 7 | **Credits:** | 2 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 4109 | **Course:** | Professional Practices | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | General | **Contact Hours:** | 2 hours/Week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | Nil | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Nil | **Lab Course Code:** | Nil | | | | |

  
|**Course Objectives** |  
|-|  
| By the end of the course, students will be able to: 1. Understand the foundations of computing professionalism, ethics, and legal responsibilities. 2. Analyze organizational structures, HR practices, software contracts, and intellectual property issues. 3. Apply professional codes of conduct and ethical frameworks (BCS, IEEE, ACM) to real-world scenarios. 4. Evaluate social, legal, and professional responsibilities of computing professionals, including auditing and accountability. | 

  
|**Course Description** |  
|-|  
|  | |

**Text/Reference Books :** 
  
|| |-| 
| 1. This course introduces students to the professional, ethical, legal, and social responsibilities of<br>2. computing professionals. Topics include computing ethics, organizational structures, software<br>3. liability, intellectual property rights, employee relations, HR management in IT, health and safety,<br>4. professional codes of conduct (BCS, IEEE, ACM), accountability, auditing, and social<br>5. applications of ethics. The course emphasizes real-world case studies and promotes critical<br>6. thinking to prepare students for responsible professional practice.<br>7. Professional Issues inSoftware Engineering by Frank Bott, Allison Coleman, Jack Eatonand Diane<br>8. Rowland, CRC Press; 3rd Edition<br>9. Computer Ethics by Deborah G. Johnson, Pearson; 4th Edition<br>10. ACM/IEEE – Software Engineering Code of Ethics and Professional Practice | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---|
| 1 | Computing Profession, Computing Ethics, Philosophy of Ethics. |
| 2 | The Structure of Organizations and its effects on Professional ethics |
| 3 | Finance and Accounting |
| 4 | Anatomy of a Software House, Computer Contracts |
| 5 | Intellectual Property Rights |
| 6 | The Framework of Employee Relations Law and Changing Management Practices |
| 7 | Human Resource Management and IT |
| 8 | Midterm Exam |
| 9 | Health and Safety at Work |
| 10 | Software Liability, Liability and Practice |
| 11 | Computer Misuse and the Criminal Law, Regulation and Control of Personal Information |
| 12 | Overview of the British Computer Society Code of Conduct, IEEE Code of Ethics |
| 13 | ACM Code of Ethics and Professional Conduct, ACM/IEEE Software Engineering Code of Ethics and Professional Practice |
| 14 | Accountability and Auditing |
| 15 | Social Application of Ethics. |

