## **CSC 4107 Information Security**  

|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Programme:** | CS/SE/AI | **Degree:** | BS | **Semester:** | 7 | **Credits:** | 2 |
| **Course Code:** | CSC 4201 | **Course:** | Information Security | **Course Type:** | Core | | |
| **Course Area/Domain:** | Computer Science | **Contact Hours:** | 2 hours/Week. | **Pre-Requisite:** | Nil | | |
| **Lab Course Name:** | Lab: Information Security | **Lab Course Code:** | CSCL 4107 | | | | |

**Course Objectives**  
  
|| |-|  
| S This course provides a comprehensive foundation in Information Assurance and Information Security. It covers core security principles, international standards, cyber security threats, preventive measures, cryptographic systems, authentication mechanisms, and network security fundamentals. Students learn to evaluate risks, analyze attacks, implement passive and active defense mechanisms, and examine security policies. The course emphasizes hands-on understanding through case studies, focusing on designing and auditing secure information systems according to industry standards. Stallings &Brown, Computer Security, Principles and Practice Whitman & Mattord, Principles of Information Security | |

  
|**Course Description** |  
|-|  
|  | |

* 
|**Text/Reference Books :* |  
|-| 
| 1. Behrouze A Forouzan, Cryptography and Network Security, McGraw Hill Publishers | |

**SYLLABUS**  
| **Week** | **Topics** |
|---|---
| 1 | Introduction to Information Assurance Information Security Principles |
| 2 | Standards of Information Assurance |
| 3 | Terms, Concepts and Tradeoffs Related to Information Security |
| 4 | Introduction to Cyber Security Cyber Security Threats and Measures |
| 5 | Cyber Security SOPs and Policies |
| 6 | Introduction to Cryptography |
| 7 | Symmetric Cryptography |
| 8 | Midterm Exam |
| 9 | Asymmetric Cryptography |
| 10 | Secure Identity, Authentication and Signature Techniques |
| 11 | Understanding Basic Network Concepts |
| 12 | Typical Network Attacks and Threats from the Internet |
| 13 | Passive Measures to Ward off Network Attacks |
| 14 | Active Measures to Safeguard an Enterprise Network |
| 15 | Case Study for Designing and Auditing a Security System |

**COURSE LEARNING OUTCOMES (CLOs)**  
| **CLO** | **Description** | **Domain** | **BT Level** |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Explain principles, standards, concepts, and trade-offs in InformationAssurance andInformationSecurity. | C | 2 |
| 2 | Identify threats and apply preventive, cryptographic, authentication,andpolicy-basedsecuritymeasures. | C | 1,3 |
| 3 | Analyze network concepts, attacks, and implement passive & active measures todesignandaudit secure networks. | C | 4 |

BT=Bloom’s Taxonomy, C=Cognitive domain, P=Psychomotor domain, A=Affective domain  

